body:
## Description

This implements multi-index context in ClearRefinements leveraging `scopedResults` (#3964).

A ClearRefinements widget now clears the refinements coming from its siblings and its children.

## Implementation

### `init` hook is now a noop

Since we now rely on the `scopedResults` given during `render`, `init` is a noop:

- It considers there are no refinements
- `refine` is a noop at this step
- `createURL` is a noop at this step

This is the reason why some tests have change from `hasRefinements: true` to `hasRefinements: false` at `init`.

### [Attributes were not deduped](https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch.js/blob/2ec09814941b9e1bbec0bdbeea31680f800a0112/src/connectors/clear-refinements/connectClearRefinements.js#L181-L196)

This didn't cause any issues for the usage of the connector but I still dedup them in the new implementation to avoid inconsistent state if we're to build on top on this feature.

In the story, if you select "Samsung", "Apple", and "Cell Phones", the result is:

```
// Old implementation
['brand', brand', 'categories']  // Length: 3 => hasRefinements === true
// New implementation
['brand', 'categories] // Length: 2 => hasRefinements === true
```

This is using `uniq` which is not very costly for the number of attributes that we need to dedup.

## Example

```js
search.addWidgets([
  instantsearch.widgets.clearRefinements({
    container,
  }),

  instantsearch.widgets
    .index({
      indexName: 'instant_search_price_asc',
    })
    .addWidgets([
      instantsearch.widgets.refinementList({
        container,
        attribute: 'brand',
      }),
    ]),

  instantsearch.widgets
    .index({
      indexName: 'instant_search_rating_asc',
    })
    .addWidgets([
      instantsearch.widgets.refinementList({
        container,
        attribute: 'categories',
      }),
    ]),
]);
```

